@niemeyer maybe i'ts my mistake. So, 

> We don't support that because Go ... Note you can set the value to 1 and have the same behavior.

That's mean, a first number what will be correct is 1000000000 time.Duration, or 1 \* time.Second. Any lesser will be equal 0. Maybe best decision: notify about incorrect value.

> We might support a mode with Delta(nil, obj1), which is closer to your requirements.

So Delta(nil, obj) would be equivalent to AsUpdate(obj) ?

That would seem reasonable.

Implementing Delta itself efficiently without doing any marshaling/unmarshaling round trippage
seems hard, because deep checking equality is going to be hard.

I can imagine a version of Delta implemented in terms of (an unexported) AsUpdate, something
like this:

```
// Delta returns the updates that will result if the object
// obj0 is updated to be obj1. It does not always return
// the most efficient update - when the values are hard
// to compare, it might result in redundant Set members.
//
// If obj1 is nil, the result will be as if obj0 was a value
// of the same type as obj0 with all fields non-zero and
// different from those in obj1.
func Delta(obj0, obj1 interface{}) (Update, error) {
    u1 := asUpdate(obj1)
    if obj0 == nil {
        return u1, nil
    }
    u0 := asUpdate(obj0)

    for attr := range u1.Unset {
        if _, ok := u0.Unset[attr]; ok {
            delete(u1.Unset, attr)
        }
    }
    for attr, val1 := range u1.Set {
        if val0, ok := u0.Set[attr]; ok && obviouslyEqual(val0, val1) {
            delete(u1.Set, attr)
        }
    }
    return u1
}

// obviouslyEqual returns true if x and y are easily comparable
// and will be equal when marshaled as BSON, and false
// otherwise.
func obviouslyEqual(x, y reflect.Value) bool {
    ...
}
```

I guess the obviouslyEqual function could fall back to marshaling and comparing
bytes for the harder cases.

I'm interested in your envisaged use cases for Delta - I haven't yet come across a situation
where something like that might be useful.

I like that idea, but I'm not sure how it can work decently. As a really simple example,  say I have the type:

```
type T struct {
    A int
    // other fields
}
```

and I have a method that wants to set A in the database. 

```
func SetA(a int) {
    old := T{ ??? }
    obj := T {A: a}
    ... := collection.Update(bson.Delta(old, obj)))
}
```

What should we set the value of old to if a can be any int? ISTM that the only way is to set old.A to any value other than a (a+1 for example) because otherwise we are not guaranteed that a will be set (or unset if A is marked as omitempty).

It feels to me like it would be more awkward in practice than just writing out the update doc.
